description.narrative: (Ethiopia): The FTF Growth Through Nutrition (GtN) activity seeks to improve the nutritional status.of women and young children in the productive regions of Ethiopia with a focus.on the first 1,000 days, a critical window of opportunity for child growth and.development. With an overarching goal of reducing stunting by 20 percent, GtN works.in 110 woredas in Amhara, Oromia, SNNP and Tigray. .With FY 2020 resources, the.activity will continue to improve the production of more diverse crops and.livestock products in order to increase dietary diversity by increasing.household access to inputs such as improved seeds, tools, and livestock. The.activity also will engage the private sector to improve the supply of both.sanitation products and services as well as agricultural inputs. In addition,.GtN will provide ongoing technical assistance to improve nutritional outcomes.through the GOE's second National Nutrition Program, and will promote and.support sustainable WASH interventions to improve community hygiene and access.to safe drinking water and better sanitation services. GtN efforts to reduce.malnutrition will contribute to reduced mortality, as malnutrition is an.underlying cause of up to half of child mortality. In addition, GtN will.improve the capacity of health sector personnel who provide maternal and child.nutrition services and enhance service quality, which will be critical as.Ethiopia grapples with a reduction in people seeking health services due to.COVID-19. Furthermore, it will support strategic nutrition learning and.assessment activities to tailor interventions to the specific context and.identify solutions to operational bottlenecks and challenges that affect GOE.nutrition interventions. Moreover, GtN will strengthen multisectoral.coordination and improve capacity to implement more effective nutrition and.WASH interventions in part through its continuing support for the.implementation of the GOE's recently approved Food and Nutrition Policy. ..
